In our CI/CD pipeline, we follow a structured approach covering build, test, security, artifact management, and GitOps-based deployment.
1️⃣ Build Stage
The pipeline starts when code is pushed to a feature or development branch.
We compile the application and resolve dependencies.
The build artifact (JAR/war/binary) is generated.
2️⃣ Unit & Functional Testing
We run:
Smoke Tests
Unit Tests
Functional / Integration Tests
Regression Tests
If any test fails, the pipeline stops.
3️⃣ Code Quality Gate
We run static code analysis using Sonar.
The build must pass quality gates (coverage %, vulnerabilities, code smells threshold).
4️⃣ Artifact Storage – JFrog
Once validated, the build artifact is pushed to JFrog Artifactory.
This becomes the single source of truth for versioned artifacts.
We use semantic versioning (e.g., 1.0.3, 1.0.4).
5️⃣ Containerization & Image Registry
A Docker image is built using the artifact.
The image is tagged with:
Build number
Git commit ID
Environment tag
The image is pushed to Harbor (our private container registry).
6️⃣ Image Security Scanning – Trivy
Before deployment, we scan the container image using Trivy.
We enforce policies:
No Critical vulnerabilities
Limited High vulnerabilities
If the vulnerability threshold is exceeded, the pipeline fails.
7️⃣ Deployment Using Helm (GitOps Model)
We use Helm charts for Kubernetes deployments.
The image tag is updated in the Helm values file.
Instead of deploying directly to Kubernetes, we follow a GitOps approach:
The updated Helm values or manifest file is committed to a higher environment branch (for example:
dev → qa → stage → prod).
Each environment has its own branch or folder.
8️⃣ Argo CD Deployment
Argo CD watches the respective branch/environment repository.
When a change is pushed (for example, image tag update), Argo CD:
Detects drift
Syncs automatically
Deploys the new version to the Kubernetes cluster.
This ensures:
Version-controlled deployments
Audit trail of changes
Easy rollback
No direct kubectl access required
Promotion Strategy 
We follow branch-based promotion:
After successful deployment in DEV,
the manifest file 
(with updated image tag) is merged to the QA branch.
After QA validation → merged to STAGE.
After business approval → merged to PROD.
So we are promoting Git commits, not rebuilding artifacts.


🧱 GitHub Actions Workflow (.github/workflows/cicd.yml)
yaml
name: CI-CD Pipeline

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - "feature/*"
      - "develop"
      - "main"

jobs:
  build-test-quality:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up JDK
        uses: actions/setup-java@v4
        with:
          java-version: "17"

      - name: Build Artifact
        run: mvn clean package -DskipTests=false

      - name: Run Unit & Functional Tests
        run: mvn test

      - name: SonarQube Analysis
        uses: sonarsource/sonarqube-scan-action@v2
        with:
          projectBaseDir: .
          args: >
            -Dsonar.projectKey=my-app
            -Dsonar.qualitygate.wait=true

      - name: Upload Artifact to JFrog
        run: |
          curl -u ${{ secrets.JFROG_USER }}:${{ secrets.JFROG_TOKEN }} \
          -T target/myapp.jar \
          "https://mycompany.jfrog.io/artifactory/libs-release-local/myapp/${{ github.run_number }}/myapp.jar"

  containerize-scan:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: build-test-quality
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Build Docker Image
        run: |
          docker build -t harbor.mycompany.com/myapp:${{ github.run_number }} .

      - name: Scan Image with Trivy
        uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@v0.14.0
        with:
          image-ref: harbor.mycompany.com/myapp:${{ github.run_number }}
          severity: CRITICAL,HIGH
          ignore-unfixed: true
          exit-code: 1

      - name: Push Image to Harbor
        run: |
          echo ${{ secrets.HARBOR_PASS }} | docker login harbor.mycompany.com -u ${{ secrets.HARBOR_USER }} --password-stdin
          docker push harbor.mycompany.com/myapp:${{ github.run_number }}

  gitops-deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: containerize-scan
    steps:
      - name: Checkout Environment Repo
        uses: actions/checkout@v4
        with:
          repository: mycompany/environment-configs
          token: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}

      - name: Update Helm Values
        run: |
          sed -i "s/tag:.*/tag: ${{ github.run_number }}/" environments/dev/values.yaml
          git config user.name "GitHub Actions"
          git config user.email "actions@github.com"
          git commit -am "Update image tag to ${{ github.run_number }}"
          git push origin dev
🚀 Argo CD Configuration (argocd-app.yaml)
yaml
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: myapp-dev
spec:
  project: default
  source:
    repoURL: https://github.com/mycompany/environment-configs.git
    targetRevision: dev
    path: environments/dev
  destination:
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
    namespace: myapp-dev
  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true
      selfHeal: true
✅ Pipeline Flow Summary
Stage	Tool	Purpose
Build	Maven	Compile & package
Test	JUnit	Validate functionality
Quality	SonarQube	Enforce code standards
Artifact	JFrog	Store versioned builds
Container	Docker + Harbor	Package & tag
Security	Trivy	Scan vulnerabilities
Deploy	Helm + Argo CD	GitOps rollout


This configuration ensures:

Automated build/test/scan/deploy with full traceability.

GitOps control — Argo CD deploys only when manifests change.

Security enforcement — Trivy blocks vulnerable images.

Versioned artifacts — JFrog and Harbor maintain immutable history.
